def comb_sort(data):
    j = 1
    gap = len(data)
    swapped = True
    while gap != 1 or swapped == True:
        gap = int(gap * 1.3)
        gap = min(gap, len(data) - 1)
        swapped = False
        for i in range(len(data) - gap):
            if data[i] > data[i + gap]:
                data[i], data[i + gap] = data[i + gap], data[i]
                swapped = True

    return data

Floating point errors are sometimes called floating point exceptions for exception handling applications. Floating-point errors are sometimes called floating point accuracy problems because the result is not an exact decimal representation of the expected floating-point result. For example, consider the following C program that adds the numbers 0.1 and 0.2:

``````
#include <stdio.h>

int main (void)
{
double f = 0.1, g = 0.2;
printf ("%.6lf + %.6lf = %.6lf\n",f, g, f + g);
}

`````

The program prints:

``````
0.10000000 + 0.20000000 = 0.30000028

`````

A calculator or other program that can use IEEE 754 64-bit binary floating-point would find the exact result:

``````
0.10000000 + 0.20000000 = 0.30000000000000004

`````

The difference is due to how computers store numbers in computer memory. The numbers 0.1 and 0.2 cannot be expressed exactly as floating point numbers because they are represented in a binary system in fractional form. However, on most computing platforms, their double precision decimal representation matches the one described above. Many programmers are surprised to learn how 0.1 + 0.2 might not be equal to 0.3.

The solution depends. Some use arbitrary precision arithmetic. Some use decimal arithmetic. Some use single precision instead of double precision. Some add a floating point comparison delta as illustrated below. For example:

``````
double f = 0.1, g = 0.2;
double delta = 0.0000000001;
printf ("%.6lf + %.6lf = %.6lf\n",f, g, f + g < 0.3 + delta);

`````

This technique will work most of the time but will not always work. Another solution is to use single precision and check for range limits:

