Eventual consistency is a property of distributed systems in which all nodes become consistent after a certain amount of time, despite temporary inconsistent states. It acknowledges that during the transient period when some nodes are up to date with the latest data and others are not, reads can provide inconsistent results. However, as long as the system is designed to recover from such inconsistencies over time, the overall consistency is eventually achieved. This design allows for faster read and write operations due to parallel processing on multiple nodes, which is particularly useful for large-scale systems. To ensure eventual consistency, careful implementation and careful management of the recovery processes are crucial. The term "eventual consistency" originated from eventual convergence, which describes how the system moves towards a state of consistency that becomes permanent over time.

For more information, refer to: https://towardsdatascience.com/get-the-basics-of-eventual-consistency-in-distributed-systems-ff31bc8af05c

